title: High yield production of the medical radioisotope 167Tm by the 167Er(d,2n)reaction

x4freetext: High yield production of the medical radioisotope
167Tm by the 167Er(d,2n)reaction

x4freetext: 20 MeV
The target samples were prepared of highly enriched
erbium-oxide, 167Er2O3 powder by sedimentation onto
Al backing of 13.0 mm diameter and 0.1 mm thickness.
The samples were covered by 0.01 mm thick Al
wrapping for protection.
Thickness of targets: 13-19 mg/cm2,
Characteristics of the erbium-oxide powder:
chemical purity: 99.6%;
isotopic composition of erbium (atom%):
Three stacks were bombarded with 20.7 MeV deuterons,
irradiation time: 1.5 h,
beam intensity: 100 nA.
The stacks contained six erbium-oxide samples
alternating with eight Ti monitor foils and were
inserted in a Faraday-cup-like target holder equipped
with a long collimator and secondary electron
suppressing device.
The beam intensity was controlled by integration of the
deposited charge in the target holder.
The extracted beam energy was estimated from the
accelerator settings.
The samples were measured non-destructively,
without chemical separation
several times after end of bombardment over aperiod of
4 months.

x4freetext: Estimation of the uncertainty on the median
energy in the samples is obtained by taking into
account the cumulative errors influencing the
energy calculation(incident deuteron energy,
sample inhomogeneity and beam energy straggling).
The uncertainty of the energy is +-0.3 MeV for
the first pellet, increasing to +-1.8 MeV at the end
of the stack.

x4freetext: The independent relative errors of the
linearly contributing processes were summed
quadratically and the square root was taken.
number of target nuclei per areaunit 5%
beam current 5%
decay parameters 5%
detector efficiency 3-5%
statistical error 1-8%
The total uncertainty on each cross section is
between 10 and 15 %.
The excitation functions of the investigated
reactions were calculated by means of the pre-compound
model codes ALICE-D and EMPIRE-D.The experimental
data are also compared with the cross section
data in the EAF 2007 and TENDL 2009 nuclear
reaction data libraries that were developed on the
base of the TALYS nuclear model code system.
Integral yields were calculated from the
fitted experimental cross sections.

x4freetext: The possible contribution of the 166Er(d,n) reaction
was neglected, considering that it does not exceed 1%.
Contribution of 168Er(d,3n) reaction was corrected.
According to the analysis, based on a comparison of
the theoretical results for the EMPIRE-D code, the
contribution of the 3.08% 168Er in the target would
increase between 1.2% at 15 MeV and about 11% at 20.4
MeV. For energies below 14 MeV the correction would be
lower than 1%.
The results were normalised to 100% 167Er target
isotope.
